{"slug": "possess", "root": "possess", "category": "act", "gloss": "to inhabit/seize a body", "definition": "To *possess*, in the magical sense, is for a spirit or demon to seize and inhabit a living body, overriding its owner's will and acting through it. It differs from *haunt*, which lingers about a place from outside: possession takes up residence *within* a person. The word carries its property-law twin — the possessing spirit occupies the body as a squatter holds ground it does not own.", "history": "Latin *possidēre*, 'to hold or occupy' (from *potis*, 'able,' + *sedēre*, 'to sit'), meant to have and hold — the root of 'property' and 'possession.' The turn is Christian: demonic *possession* recast that legal 'holding' as a spirit literally *sitting in* a body, an occupying tenant to be expelled. The medieval and Renaissance record treats it as a clinical category — Fanger reads one saint's career as beginning in a more ordinary case of demonic possession, and reformers staged spectacular exorcisms of those considered possessed by demons. Magic: The Gathering keeps the seizing, body-taking sense.", "def_sources": [{"label": "Bailey et al., The Sacred and the Sinister (case of demonic possession)", "where": "Medieval magic (PDF)"}, {"label": "Zambelli, White Magic (exorcism of those possessed by demons)", "where": "Renaissance magic (PDF)"}, {"label": "Etymonline, s.v. possess", "where": "Etymology reference"}], "commentary": null, "commentary_sources": [], "is_keyword": false, "etymology": {"lang": "Latin", "origin": "Latin possidēre 'to hold, occupy' (potis 'able' + sedēre 'to sit')", "first": "late 14c.", "note": "Demonic possession is a spirit 'sitting in' the body — the same root that gives us 'property' and 'possession'.", "hook": "The property law inside demonic possession."}, "essay": null, "sources": ["Etymonline (Douglas Harper)", "Wiktionary", "classical lexica (Lewis & Short, LSJ, Bosworth–Toller)", "Ted's historical-magic DBs (WitchcraftStudiesDB, 